etymologies: mid 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Blundeville (fl. 1561), author and translator. From classical Latin prōcidentia displacement of an organ of the body, prolapse (Pliny) from prōcident-, prōcidēns, present participle of prōcidere to fall forward + -ia

definitions: Prolapse of an organ, specifically of the rectum (more fully "†procidentia ani", "procidentia recti") or uterus (more fully "procidentia uteri"); an instance of this.
